@shazow @paulg Yes! Agree 100%. We're hardwired to notice inconsistency. Brings focus to the problem much faster.
@corduroy @bmatt a) don't do that. b) when you do that, fix it as soon as you realize. c) make it part of your personal and work ethic.

@ericholscher @paulg Yes, absolutely! Think of your future self!
@ggreer I totally disagree. I'd rather have even poorly written, inaccurate docs than no docs. At least it gives me a place to start.
@jmendeth @fxn I'd consider any change from inputs to outputs to be the "action" of a function. What's your definition of "action"?
@paulg Yes! But there is also a temporal component. What is obvious to the coder NOW may be very much non-obvious to a reader years later.
@TheMikeJang I'm still confused. Do you consider DNA sufficiently self-documenting, or as a critical comparison to undocumented code?
@lrbpx I disagree. Tests may show me how to USE some code, but don't give me much insight into the internals of that code.
@jmendeth @fxn I disagree. Code rarely tells you WHY it's doing what it's doing, or how it fits into the bigger picture of the program.
Code comments are especially important for open source projects, where interested folks quite likely are not experts in the language used.
@TheMikeJang Not sure I follow. Are you suggesting that DNA *is* self documenting?
@nicosetton That would be great, but it's just not going to happen in most languages.
I guarantee that commenting your code is easier AND better than trying to write perfectly self-documenting code.
@rjstanley You wouldn't have to, if you'd just do the easy thing and comment your code!
@rjstanley I dare you to go back and look at undocumented code you wrote a year ago and tell me it's sufficiently self-documenting. =)
@paulg As a non-LISP native, I bet a simple code comment on that would get me to comprehension much faster. =)
@rjstanley That's fine. I'd much rather have a lot of non-perfect docs than no docs. It's all about getting to comprehension faster.
Code comments should get me to a 75% understanding of the code. The code gets me to 100%. An occasional incorrect comment is no big deal.
@paulg Haha, touch√©. Now try it for any non-trivial function.
@hmemcpy Oh good! Rock on.
@mattpodwysocki @dries139 Excellent policy!
@hmemcpy Unlikely. Maybe 1.1-2x longer, but that's very much worth it to reduce time-to-comprehension for later developers in the code.
@dries139 @mattpodwysocki By being a responsible, professional developer and updating comments when code changes.
Self-documenting code is a myth. Code only communicates action, not intent. Nor does it communicate assumptions about input constraints.
Want to become a 10x better coder overnight? It's easy! DOCUMENT YOUR CODE.
